# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: swift-banking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] A **correspondent account** is an account (often called a nostro or vostro account) established by a banking institution to receive deposits from, make payments on behalf of, or handle other financial transactions for another financial institution.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] Correspondent accounts are established through bilateral agreements between the two banks.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] Commonly, correspondent accounts are the accounts of foreign banks that require the ability to pay and receive the domestic currency.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] A bank will typically require correspondent accounts for holding currencies outside of jurisdictions where it has a branch or affiliate.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] This is because most central bank settlement systems do not register deposits or transfer funds to banks not doing business in their countries.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] With few exceptions, the actual funds held in any foreign currency account (whether for a bank or for its customer) are held in the bank's correspondent account in that currency's home country.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] Even where a bank has branches or affiliates in multiple jurisdictions, balances in a foreign currency account in one jurisdiction are held with a correspondent account at either that bank's branch or affiliate in the foreign country, or at another institution.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] For example, HSBC receives US dollars at its affiliate, HSBC Bank USA, while DBS Bank Singapore receives US dollars at JPMorgan Chase.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] A Dutch oil company is a customer of ING in Amsterdam, and sells a cargo of 500,000 barrels of oil for $40 million to a Swiss trading company who is a customer of Credit Suisse.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] ING Amsterdam holds its dollars at Bank of America (BofA) and Credit Suisse holds its dollars at The Bank of New York Mellon (BNY).
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] When the Swiss trader instructs its bank to pay the money, Credit Suisse debits the trader's account and transfers dollars from its correspondent account at BNY to ING's account at BofA.
[src:swift-banking/correspondent-account] Then, ING credits the dollars to the oil company's dollar account in Amsterdam.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] The overlapping issue between ISO 9362 and ISO 13616 is discussed in the article International Bank Account Number (also called IBAN).
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] The SWIFT network does not require a specific format for the transaction so the identification of accounts and transaction types is left to agreements of the transaction partners.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] In the process of the Single Euro Payments Area the European central banks have agreed on a common format based on IBAN and BIC including an XML-based transmission format for standardized transactions.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] T2 (RTGS) is a joint gross clearing system in the European Union that does not require the SWIFT network for transmission (see EBICS).
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] The TARGET directory lists all the BICs of the banks that are attached to the TARGET2-network being a subset of the SWIFT-directory of BICs.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] ISO 9362 is based on the industry standard created by SWIFT around 1975.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Where an eight character code is given, it may be assumed that it refers to the primary office.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] SWIFT Standards, a division of The Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication (SWIFT), handles the registration of these codes.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Because SWIFT originally introduced what was later standardized as Business Identifier Codes (BICs), they are still often called SWIFT addresses or codes.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] The 2009 update of ISO 9362 broadened the scope to include non-financial institutions; before then BIC was commonly understood to be an acronym for *Bank Identifier Code*.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] There are over 7,500 "live" codes (for partners actively connected to the SWIFT network) and an estimated 10,000 additional BIC codes which can be used for manual transactions.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Deutsche Bank is an international bank, with its head office in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Deutsche Bank uses an extended code of 11 characters and has assigned branches or processing areas individual extended codes.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] This allows the payment to be directed to a specific office.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] For example, DEUTDEFF500 would direct the payment to an office of Deutsche Bank in Bad Homburg.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Nedbank is a primarily South African bank, with its head office in Johannesburg.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Nedbank has not implemented the extended code of 11 characters and all SWIFT transfers to its accounts are directed to the primary office for processing.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Those transfer interfaces that require an 11 digit code would enter NEDSZAJJXXX.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Danske Bank is a primarily Danish bank, with its head office in Copenhagen.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] UniCredit Banca is a primarily Italian bank with its head office in Milan.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Dah Sing Bank is a bank based in Hong Kong that has five branches in mainland China (primary mainland China branch in Shenzhen).
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] The SWIFT code for the branch in Shanghai is DSBACNBXSHA.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] It uses the 11-digit extended code, and SHA identifies the Shanghai branch.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] BDO Unibank is the biggest bank in the Philippines, with its head office in Makati.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] All BDO branches have the same SWIFT Code.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Note that one bank can seem to have more than one bank identifier in a given country for separation purposes.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Bank of East Asia separates its representative branch in the US and its US-based operations for local customers into BEASUS33xxx (following the code used in its home country) and BEAKUS33xxx respectively.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] This differs from its local mainland China operations which are also BEASCNxxxxx following Hong Kong rather than having a separate identifier code.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] In the past, SEPA payments required both BIC and IBAN.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Since 2016-02-01 only the IBAN is needed inside the SEPA (European Union and some more countries).
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] To identify endpoints on its network, SWIFT also uses twelve-character codes that are derived from the BIC of the institution.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Such a code consists of the 'BIC8', followed by a one-character code that identifies the Logical Terminal (LT), (also referred to as "local destination" or "Logical Terminal address"), and the three-character branch code.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] While 'BIC12's are not part of the ISO standard, and are only relevant in the context of the messaging platform, they play a role in FIN system messaging.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] According to SWIFT, Logical Terminals are the "entity through which users send and receive FIN messages.", thus, may play a role within routing of the message.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Business Identifier Codes are primarily used for identifying financial and non-financial institutions involving day-to-day business transactions among one or more institutions in transaction lifecycle.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Example: In SWIFT messages these BICs are embedded within the messages.
[src:swift-banking/iso-9362] Consider the message type for cash transfer MT103, here we can find BIC under different tags like 50a (ordering customer), 56a (intermediary), 57a (account with institution), etc.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] A **payment system** is any system used to settle financial transactions through the transfer of monetary value.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This includes the institutions, payment instruments such as payment cards, people, rules, procedures, standards, and technologies that make its exchange possible.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] A payment system is an operational network which links bank accounts and provides for monetary exchange using bank deposits.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Some payment systems also include credit mechanisms, which are essentially a different aspect of payment.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Payment systems are used in lieu of tendering cash in domestic and international transactions.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This consists of a major service provided by banks and other financial institutions.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Traditional payment systems include negotiable instruments such as drafts (e.g., cheques) and documentary credits such as letters of credit.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] With the advent of computers and electronic communications, many alternative electronic payment systems have emerged.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The term **electronic payment** refers to a payment made from one bank account to another using electronic methods and forgoing the direct intervention of bank employees.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Narrowly defined electronic payment refers to e-commerce—a payment for buying and selling goods or services offered through the Internet, or broadly to any type of electronic funds transfer.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Modern payment systems use cash-substitutes as compared to traditional payment systems.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This includes debit cards, credit cards, electronic funds transfers, direct credits, direct debits, internet banking, e-commerce payment systems and Buy now, pay later (BNPL).
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] More recently, protocol-level payment mechanisms have emerged as alternatives to account-based models.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The x402 open standard repurposes the HTTP 402 "Payment Required" status code to enable payments directly within the HTTP request–response cycle, eliminating the need for user accounts, sessions, or traditional payment intermediaries.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Payment systems may be physical or electronic and each has its own procedures and protocols.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Standardization has allowed some of these systems and networks to grow to a global scale, but there are still many country-specific and product-specific systems.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Examples of payment systems that have become globally available are credit card and automated teller machine (ATM) networks.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Additionally, forms exist to transfer funds between financial institutions.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Domestically this is accomplished by using Automated clearing house (ACH) and real-time gross settlement (RTGS) systems.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Internationally this is accomplished by correspondent banking (possibly using the SWIFT network) or a more centralised system like the CLS settlement system.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] An efficient national payment system reduces the cost of exchanging goods, services, and assets.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] It is indispensable to the functioning of the interbank, money, and capital markets.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] A weak payment system may severely drag on the stability and developmental capacity of a national economy.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Such failures can result in inefficient use of financial resources, inequitable risk-sharing among agents, actual losses for participants, and loss of confidence in the financial system and in the very use of money.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The technical efficiency of the payment system is important for the development of the economy.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] An automated clearing house (ACH) system processes transactions in batches, storing, and transmitting them in groups.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] An ACH is considered a net settlement system, which means settlement may be delayed.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This poses what is known as settlement risk.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Real-time gross settlement systems (RTGS) are funds transfer systems where the transfer of money or securities takes place from one bank to another on a "real-time" and on "gross" basis.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Settlement in "real time" means that payment transaction does not require any waiting period.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The transactions are settled as soon as they are processed.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] "Gross settlement" means the transaction is settled on one to one basis without bunching or netting with any other transaction.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Once processed, payments are final and irrevocable.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Comparatively, ACHs are typically used for low-value, non-urgent transactions while RTGS systems are typically used for high-value, urgent transactions.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Countries and regions have also implemented real-time or instant (or faster) payment systems which typically operate 24x7x365 and perform the transaction from debit of ordering customer's account to credit of beneficiary customer's account within a timeframe of 10–15 seconds.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] International payment systems operate like their domestic counterparts but have additional complexity as they need to navigate currency exchange and cross-border jurisdictional and financial environments.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The key system used for international transfer has been the SWIFT network that is used by banks to transfer funds between countries.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] International transfers have traditionally been cumbersome, error prone and expensive.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Increasing globalization has driving corporations and individuals to transact more frequently across borders.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Transaction volume continue to increase with people buying from foreign eCommerce sites as well as traveling, living, and working abroad.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] For the payments industry, the result is higher volumes of payments—in terms of both currency value and number of transactions.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This is also leading to a consequent shift downwards in the average value of these payments.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Payments systems set up decades ago might be retrofitted or force-fitted to meet modern business needs.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Frequently, the systems become unstable or less reliable, for example, STEP2 (an upgrade from 2003), which processes only euros.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This has led to new transfer services that use financial technology or cryptocurrency to make it easier, faster and cheaper to transfer funds internationally.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] As of 2014, STEP2 is the only Pan-European automated clearing house (or PE-ACH system) in operation.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] This type of system is thought to become less relevant as banks will settle their transactions via multiple clearing houses rather than using one central clearing house.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] T2 is a RTGS system that covers the European Union member states which use the euro.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] It is part of the Eurosystem, which comprises the European Central Bank and the national central banks of those countries that have adopted the euro.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] T2 is used for the settlement of central bank operations, large-value Euro interbank transfers as well as other euro payments.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] It provides real-time financial transfers, debt settlement at central banks which is immediate and irreversible.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] For users of these systems, on both the paying and receiving sides, it can be difficult and time-consuming to learn how to use cross-border payment tools, and how to set up processes to make optimal use of them.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] Solution providers (both banks and non-banks) also face challenges cobbling together old systems to meet new demands.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] For these providers, cross-border payments are both lucrative (especially given foreign exchange conversion revenue) and rewarding, in terms of the overall financial relationship created with the end customer.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] The challenges for global payments are not simply those resulting from volume increases.
[src:swift-banking/payment-system] A number of economic, political, and technical factors are changing the types of cross-border transactions conducted.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The **Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication** (**SWIFT**), legally **S.W.I.F.T.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SC**, is a cooperative established in 1973 in Belgium (French: *Société Coopérative*) and owned by the banks and other member firms that use its service.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT provides the main messaging network through which international payments are initiated.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It also sells software and services to financial institutions, mostly for use on its proprietary "SWIFTNet", and assigns ISO 9362 Business Identifier Codes (BICs), popularly known as "SWIFT codes".
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT is headquartered in La Hulpe near Brussels.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It hosts an annual conference, called Sibos, specifically aimed at the financial services industry.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Before SWIFT's establishment, international financial transactions were communicated over Telex, a public system involving manual writing and reading of messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The collapse of the Bretton Woods agreement in 1971, the decoupling of the US dollar's convertibility to gold, a period in economic history now known as the "Nixon shock", shifted major currencies to floating exchange rates and increased the volume of cross-border transactions.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] That in addition to already increasing amounts of international trade made the existing Telex system insufficient.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In this novel period of international trade in a floating exchange rate environment, SWIFT was set up out of fear of what might happen if a single private and fully American entity controlled global financial flows – which before was First National City Bank (FNCB) of New York – later Citibank.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In response to FNCB's protocol, FNCB's competitors in the US and Europe pushed an alternative "messaging system that could replace the public providers and speed up the payment process".
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT was founded in Brussels on 3 May 1973.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Individuals who played a key role in its creation included bankers Jan Kraa (at AMRO Bank) and François Dentz (at the Banque de l'Union Parisienne) as well as Carl Reuterskiöld and Bessel Kok, who became respectively its first two chairmen and chief executives.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It was initially supported by 239 banks in 15 countries.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It soon started to establish common standards for financial transactions and a shared data processing system and worldwide communications network designed by Logica and developed by the Burroughs Corporation.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Fundamental operating procedures and rules for liability were established in 1975, and the first message was ceremonially sent by Prince Albert of Belgium on 9 May 1977.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT's first non-European operations centre was inaugurated by Governor John N.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In 1989 SWIFT completed a monumental new head office building in La Hulpe, designed by Ricardo Bofill Taller de Arquitectura.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The 25 directors are elected by the shareholders, on three-year terms with the renewal of one-third of the board every year; all directors are member representatives.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT acts as a carrier of the "messages containing the payment instructions between financial institutions involved in a transaction".
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] However, the organisation does not manage accounts on behalf of individuals or financial institutions, and it does not hold funds from third parties.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It also does not perform clearing or settlement functions.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] After payment has been initiated, it must be settled through a payment system, such as T2 in Europe.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In the context of cross-border transactions, this step often takes place through correspondent banking accounts that financial institutions have with each other.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] 3. a set of connection software and services allowing financial institutions to transmit messages over SWIFT network.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Under 3 above, SWIFT provides turn-key solutions for members, consisting of linkage clients to facilitate connectivity to the SWIFT network and CBTs or "computer-based terminals" which members use to manage the delivery and receipt of their messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] There are four key areas that SWIFT services fall under in the financial marketplace: securities, treasury & derivatives, trade services, and payments & cash management.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT Ref, the global payment reference data utility, is SWIFT's reference data service.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT Ref sources data from central banks, code issuers and banks.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The SWIFT secure messaging network is run from three data centres, located in the United States, the Netherlands, and Switzerland.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] These centres share information in near real-time.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In case of a failure in one of the data centres, another is able to handle the traffic of the complete network.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT uses submarine communications cables to transmit its data.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Shortly after opening its third data centre in Switzerland in 2009, SWIFT introduced a new distributed architecture with two messaging zones, European and Trans-Atlantic, so data from European SWIFT members no longer mirrored the US data centre.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] European zone messages are stored in the Netherlands and in part of the Swiss operating centre; Trans-Atlantic zone messages are stored in the United States and in another part of the Swiss operating centre that is segregated from the European zone messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Countries outside of Europe were by default allocated to the Trans-Atlantic zone but could choose to have their messages stored in the European zone.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT moved to its current IP network infrastructure, known as SWIFTNet, from 2001 to 2005, providing a total replacement of the previous X.25 infrastructure.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The process involved the development of new protocols that facilitate efficient messaging, using existing and new message standards.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The adopted technology chosen to develop the protocols was XML, which now provides a wrapper around all messages legacy or contemporary.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT provides a centralized store-and-forward mechanism, with some transaction management.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] For bank A to send a message to bank B with a copy or authorization involving institution C, it formats the message according to standards and securely sends it to SWIFT.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT guarantees its secure and reliable delivery to B after the appropriate action by C.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT guarantees are based primarily on high redundancy of hardware, software, and people.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] During 2007 and 2008, the entire SWIFT network migrated its infrastructure to a new protocol called SWIFTNet Phase 2.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The main difference between Phase 2 and the former arrangement is that Phase 2 requires banks connecting to the network to use a Relationship Management Application (RMA) instead of the former bilateral key exchange (BKE) system.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] RMA completely replaced BKE on 1 January 2009.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT has become the industry standard for syntax in financial messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Messages formatted to SWIFT standards can be read and processed by many well-known financial processing systems, whether or not the message travelled over the SWIFT network.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT cooperates with international organizations to define standards for message format and content.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In RFC 3615 *urn:swift:* was defined as Uniform Resource Names (URNs) for SWIFT FIN.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT is not a payment system and thus neither regulated nor supervised as such, but is nevertheless deemed to be systemically important and thus under the "oversight" of public authorities.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The oversight focuses primarily on systemic risk, confidentiality, infrastructure security, and business continuity.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It is formalized in bilateral documents between the NBB and SWIFT on the one hand, and between the NBB and each of the other G10 central banks on the other hand.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In 2012, this framework was complemented by a "SWIFT Oversight Forum" including additional central banks.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] As of 2024, in addition to the G10 central banks, the SWIFT Oversight Forum included the national central banks of Argentina, Australia, Brazil, China, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia, Korea, Mexico, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, South Africa, Spain, and Turkey.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] CIPS: sponsored by China, for RMB-related deals.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] 1467 financial institutions in 111 countries and regions have connected to the system.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The actual business covers more than 4,200 banking institutions in 182 countries and regions around the world.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Pix (payment system): developed by Brazil.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT has been criticised for inefficiency.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In 2018, the London-based *Financial Times* noted that transfers frequently "pass through multiple banks before reaching their final destination, making them time-consuming, costly and lacking transparency on how much money will arrive at the other end".
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SWIFT has since introduced an improved service called "Global Payments Innovation" (GPI), claiming it was adopted by 165 banks and was completing half its payments within 30 minutes.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The new standard which included SWIFT Go was supposed to be utilised in receiving and transferring low-value international payments.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] One of the significant changes was the transaction amount, which would not differ from start to end.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] For instance, Alisherov Eraj, Alif Bank Treasury Department SWIFT Transfers & Banking Relationship Expert in the Republic of Tajikistan, describes that the leading cause for the late SWIFT Go adoption in Tajikistan was the Core Banking System itself.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] To connect to SWIFT Go, he adds, banking system interfaces needed to be upgraded and integrated with their software to be fully compatible; this hindered many banks from adopting the technology earlier.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] After the publication of these articles, SWIFT quickly came under pressure for compromising the data privacy of its customers by allowing governments to gain access to sensitive personal information.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In September 2006, the Belgian government declared that these SWIFT dealings with American governmental authorities were a breach of Belgian and European privacy laws.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In response, and to satisfy members' concerns about privacy, SWIFT began a process of improving its architecture by implementing a distributed architecture with a two-zone model for storing messages .
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Concurrently, the European Union negotiated an agreement with the United States government to permit the transfer of intra-EU SWIFT transaction information to the United States under certain circumstances.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] An interim agreement was signed without European Parliamentary approval by the European Council on 30 November 2009, the day before the Lisbon Treaty—which would have prohibited such an agreement from being signed under the terms of the codecision procedure—formally came into effect.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] While the interim agreement was scheduled to come into effect on 1 January 2010, the text of the agreement was classified as "EU Restricted" until translations could be provided in all EU languages and published on 25 January 2010.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] On 11 February 2010, the European Parliament decided to reject the interim agreement between the EU and the US by 378 to 196 votes.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] One week earlier, the parliament's civil liberties committee had already rejected the deal, citing legal reservations.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In January 2012, the advocacy group United Against Nuclear Iran (UANI) implemented a campaign calling on SWIFT to end all relations with Iran's banking system, including the Central Bank of Iran.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] UANI asserted that Iran's membership in SWIFT violated US and EU financial sanctions against Iran as well as SWIFT's own corporate rules.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Consequently, in February 2012, the US Senate Banking Committee unanimously approved sanctions against SWIFT aimed at pressuring it to terminate its ties with blacklisted Iranian banks.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Expelling Iranian banks from SWIFT would potentially deny Iran access to billions of dollars in revenue using SWIFT but not from using IVTS.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Mark Wallace, president of UANI, praised the Senate Banking Committee.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Initially SWIFT denied that it was acting illegally, but later said that "it is working with U.S. and European governments to address their concerns that its financial services are being used by Iran to avoid sanctions and conduct illicit business".
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Targeted banks would be—amongst others—Saderat Bank of Iran, Bank Mellat, Post Bank of Iran and Sepah Bank.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In February 2016, most Iranian banks reconnected to the network following the lift of sanctions due to the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In November 2024, Iran implemented a paradigm shift approach to shift the focus from the SWIFT payment system by initiating the concept of bringing ACUMER.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] ACUMER was coined by Iran as a retaliation to the international sanctions imposed by the United States which has ever since limited Iran's competitive edge in the context of international trade.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Iran had long conceived an idea of bringing a viable alternative option to SWIFT in order to actively engage in smooth economic activities and international trade.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In 2014, SWIFT rejected calls from pro-Palestinian activists to revoke Israeli banks' access to its network owing to the Israeli occupation of Palestinian territory.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Similarly, in August 2014 the UK planned to press the EU to block Russian use of SWIFT as a sanction due to Russian military intervention in Ukraine.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] SPFS, a Russian alternative to SWIFT, was developed by the Central Bank of Russia as a backup measure.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] During the prelude to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the United States developed preliminary possible sanctions against Russia, but excluded banning Russia from SWIFT.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the foreign ministers of the Baltic states Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia called for Russia to be cut off from SWIFT.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] However, other EU member states were reluctant, both because European lenders held most of the nearly $30 billion in foreign banks' exposure to Russia and because Russia had developed the SPFS alternative.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The European Union, United Kingdom, Canada, and the United States finally agreed to remove a few Russian banks from the SWIFT messaging system in response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine; the governments of France, Germany, Italy and Japan individually released statements alongside the EU.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] On 20 March 2023, Russia was banned from SWIFT.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] The European Union issued the first set of sanctions against Belarus; the first was introduced on 27 February 2022, which banned certain categories of Belarusian items in the EU, including timber, steel, mineral fuels and tobacco.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] After the Lithuanian prime minister proposed disconnecting Belarus from SWIFT, the European Union, which does not recognise Lukashenko as the legitimate President of Belarus, started to plan an extension of the sanctions already issued against Russian entities and top officials to its ally.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In 2016 an $81 million theft from the Bangladesh central bank via its account at the New York Federal Reserve Bank was traced to hacker penetration of SWIFT's Alliance Access software, according to a *New York Times* report.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] It was not the first such attempt, the society acknowledged, and the security of the transfer system was undergoing new examination accordingly.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Soon after the reports of the theft from the Bangladesh central bank, a second, apparently related, attack was reported to have occurred at a commercial bank in Vietnam.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Both attacks involved malware written both to issue unauthorized SWIFT messages and to conceal that the messages had been sent.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] After the malware sent the SWIFT messages that stole the funds, it deleted the database record of the transfers and then took further steps to prevent confirmation messages from revealing the theft.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In the Bangladeshi case, the confirmation messages would have appeared on a paper report; the malware altered the paper reports when they were sent to the printer.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In the second case, the bank used a PDF report; the malware altered the PDF viewer to hide the transfers.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In May 2016, Banco del Austro (BDA) in Ecuador sued Wells Fargo after Wells Fargo honoured $12 million in fund transfer requests that had been placed by thieves.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In this case, the thieves sent SWIFT messages that resembled recently cancelled transfer requests from BDA, with slightly altered amounts; the reports do not detail how the thieves gained access to send the SWIFT messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] BDA asserts that Wells Fargo should have detected the suspicious SWIFT messages, which were placed outside of normal BDA working hours and were of an unusual size.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Wells Fargo claims that BDA is responsible for the loss, as the thieves gained access to the legitimate SWIFT credentials of a BDA employee and sent fully authenticated SWIFT messages.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In the first half of 2016, an anonymous Ukrainian bank and others—even "dozens" that are not being made public—were variously reported to have been "compromised" through the SWIFT network and to have lost money.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] In March 2022, Swiss newspaper *Neue Zürcher Zeitung* reported about the increased security precautions by the State Police of Thurgau at the SWIFT data centre in Diessenhofen.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] After most of the Russian banks had been excluded from the private payment system, the risk of sabotage was considered higher.
[src:swift-banking/society-for-worldwide-interbank-financial-telecommunication] Inhabitants of the town described the large complex as a "fortress" or "prison" where frequent security checks of the fenced property are conducted.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Different wire transfer systems and operators provide a variety of options relative to the immediacy and finality of settlement and the cost, value, and volume of transactions.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Central bank wire transfer systems, such as the Federal Reserve's Fedwire system in the United States, are more likely to be real-time gross settlement (RTGS) systems, as they provide the quickest availability of funds.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] This is because RTGS systems, such as Fedwire, post each transaction individually and immediately to the electronic accounts of participating banks maintained by the central bank.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Other systems, such as the Clearing House Interbank Payments System (CHIPS), provide net settlement on a periodic basis.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] More immediate settlement systems tend to process higher monetary value time-critical transactions, have higher transaction costs, and have a smaller volume of payments.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] A faster settlement process allows less time for currency fluctuations while money is in transit.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The first widely used service for wire transfers was launched by Western Union in 1872 on its existing telegraph network.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Once a sender had paid money to one telegraph office, the operator could transmit a message and "wire" the money to another office, using passwords and code books to authorize the release of the funds to a recipient at that location.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] By 1877 the service was used to transfer almost $2.5 million each year.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Because the earliest wire transfers were using telegraph networks, it was termed telegraphic transfer and this name is still used in some countries.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The sending bank transmits a message, via a secure system (such as SWIFT or Fedwire), to the receiving bank, requesting that it effect payment according to the instructions given.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The message also includes settlement instructions.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The actual transfer is not instantaneous: funds may take several hours or even days to move from the sender's account to the receiver's account.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Either the banks involved must hold a reciprocal account with each other, or the payment must be sent to a bank with such an account, a correspondent bank, for further benefit to the ultimate recipient.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Banks collect payment for the service from the sender as well as from the recipient.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The sending bank typically collects a fee separate from the funds being transferred, while the receiving bank and intermediary banks through which the transfer travels deduct fees from the money being transferred so that the recipient receives less than what the sender sent.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] For international wire transfers, additional information may be required, such as the recipient’s full name, physical address, bank name and address, bank account number and type, bank routing number, and the bank's SWIFT or IBAN code.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The fees and processing times can vary depending on the service provider and the destination country.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Banks may charge fees for wire transfers.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The exact fees vary widely depending on the type of payment and the type of bank accounts involved.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In some jurisdictions the fees may be regulated or capped.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Since 2009 the European Union Regulation No 924/2009 controls cross-border payments in the European Union.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In the new regulation Article 1 (q.v., Ref.4) states that an IBAN/BIC transfer within Single Euro Payments Area (SEPA) must not cost more than a national transfer, no matter which currency is used.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The receiving bank can charge for exchanging to local currency.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] As of 2022, most European banks do not charge private customers for SEPA transfers, apart from possible exchange fees.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] For business accounts, fees may be charged, but usually less than 40 cents.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Prior to this, in 2002 the European Union relegated the regulation of fees a bank may charge for payments in euro between EU member states down to the domestic level, resulting in very low or no fees for electronic transfers within the Eurozone.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In 2005, Iceland, Liechtenstein, and Norway joined the EU regulation on electronic transfers.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] However, this regulation was superseded by the Single Euro Payments Area (SEPA), consisting of 32 European countries.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In the United States, domestic wire transfers are governed by Federal Regulation J and by Article 4A of the Uniform Commercial Code.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In 2016, among the 15 largest retail banks, the average fee for an outgoing domestic wire was $25.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Incoming domestic wire fees were about evenly split between $0 (free) and $15.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Domestic transfers in Australia are generally free to consumers.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] International transfers can be costly, and banks will often charge a fee between $0 (free) and $30, and an FX margin (the difference between the interbank rate, and the rate that you are charged).
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Cheaper alternatives to the banks are available from foreign exchange brokers, who usually charge a lower fee and/or margin.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] With bank-to-bank wire transfer, each account holder must have a proven identity.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Unlike credit card payments, wire transfers can generally not be recalled (though recalls are possible in some cases and jurisdictions).
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Information contained in wires is transmitted securely through encrypted communications methods.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Wire transfers done through cash offices are essentially anonymous and are designed for transfer between persons who trust each other.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] It is unsafe to send money by wire to an unknown person to collect at a cash office; the receiver of the money may, after collecting it, not provide whatever goods or services they promised in return for the payment, but instead simply disappear.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] This scam has been used often, especially in the so-called *419 scams* which often nominate Western Union for collection.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] If a financial institution suspects that funds are being sent from or to one of these entities, it must block the transfer and freeze the funds.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] SWIFT wire transfers are not completely free of vulnerabilities.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Every intermediary bank that handles a wire transaction can take a fee directly out of the wire payload (the assets being transferred) without the account holder's knowledge or consent.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] In many places, there is no legislation or technical means to protect customers from this practice.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Clients are sometimes taken by surprise when less money arrives at bank R.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Contrast this with cheques, where the amount transferred is guaranteed in full, and fees (if there are any) can be charged only at endpoint banks.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] The European Union offers some partial protection from this practice by prohibiting European intermediary banks from taking a fee out of the amount being transferred, even for transatlantic transfers.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] However, it is still common practice for a European brokerage firm to state that they charge no transfer fee, and then contact their bank to take an unpublished fee from the amount transferred as a means to compensate their bank with their clients' assets.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] One of the largest companies that offer wire transfer is Western Union, which allows individuals to transfer or receive money without an account with Western Union or any financial institution.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Concern and controversy about Western Union transfers have increased in recent years, because of the increased monitoring of money-laundering transactions, as well as concern about terrorist groups using the service, particularly in the wake of the September 11, 2001, attacks.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Although Western Union keeps information about senders and receivers, some transactions can be done essentially anonymously, for the receiver is not always required to show identification.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Another option for consumers and businesses transferring money internationally is to use specialised brokerage houses for their international money transfer needs.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Many of these specialised brokerage houses can transfer money at better exchange rates compared to banks, thus saving up to 4%.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] These providers can offer a range of currency exchange products like spot contracts, forward contracts and limit orders.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] However, not all such providers are regulated by appropriate government bodies.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] For example, in the UK, even though such companies are regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority, not all of them fall under FCA scrutiny.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Other such regulators include the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC), the Financial Transactions Reports Analysis Centre of Canada (FINTRAC) in Canada, and the Hong Kong Customs and Excise Department.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Most international transfers are executed through SWIFT, a co-operative society founded in 1974 by seven international banks, which operate a global network to facilitate the transfer of financial messages.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Using these messages, banks can exchange data for the transfer of funds between financial institutions.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] SWIFT's headquarters are in La Hulpe, on the outskirts of Brussels, Belgium.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] SWIFT also acts as an international standards body for the creation and maintenance of financial-messaging standards.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Each financial institution is assigned an ISO 9362 code, also called a *Bank Identifier Code* (*BIC*) or *SWIFT Code*.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] These codes are generally eight characters long.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Using an extended code of 11 digits (if the receiving bank has assigned extended codes to branches or to processing areas) allows the payment to be directed to a specific office.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] For example: DEUTDEFF500 would direct the payment to an office of Deutsche Bank in Bad Homburg.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] SWIFT deviates slightly from the standard, though, by using position nine for a Logical Terminal ID, making its extended codes 12 digits long.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] European banks making transfers within the European Union and within Switzerland also use the International Bank Account Number, or IBAN.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Banks in the United States use SWIFT to send messages to notify banks in other countries that a payment has been made.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Banks use the Fedwire system or CHIPS to actually effect the payment.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Domestic bank-to-bank wire transfers are conducted through Fedwire or CHIPS.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Transmitting and receiving US banks are uniquely identified by their ABA routing transit number.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] Other forms of electronic transfers include, for example, electronic funds transfer system (EFTS).
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] This is the system used to transfer money from a bank account to another party.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] It is also the system used in some payments made via a bank's online bill payment service.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] These transfers are made using a bank routing number and the account number at that institution.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] EFTS transfers differ from wire transfers in important legal ways.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] An EFTS payment is essentially an electronic personal check, whereas a wire transfer is more like an electronic cashier's check.
[src:swift-banking/wire-transfer] EFTS transfers are often called "ACH transfers", because they take place through Automated Clearing Houses.
